<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1923-05-04T12:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1923-05-04T12:00:00-05:00" n="134" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d134">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">611.629 Ruhr/24: Telegram</note>
                        <head><hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in France</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Herrick</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to
                                the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss></hi></head>
                        <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Paris</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1923-05-04T17:00:00+00:00"><hi rend="italic">May 4, 1923—5
                                        p.m.</hi></date><lb/>[Received May 4—3:52
                            p.m.]</dateline></opener>
                        <p>232. Your 173, April 28, 5 p.m.</p>
                        <p>Commercial attaché suggests that he be authorized to issue informal
                            letter forwarded to American buyers in the occupied regions for
                            presentation to the Rhineland Interallied High Commission expressing his
                            appreciation of any courtesies in issuing exportation permits. Such
                            letters would not give guarantee of any kind by commercial attaché. We
                            are agreed that the letters may relieve the severe losses being suffered
                            by American houses pending the settlement of the question with the
                            Foreign Office.</p>
                        <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Herrick</hi></signed></closer>
                    </div>
